Big Data modelling with mgcv and mgcViz

Matteo Fasiolo

October 06 2023

The main Big Data fitting functions we are going to use are:

  • bam() from the mgcv package fits an GAM models, and returns an object of class gam. See ?gamObject.
  • bamV() from the mgcViz package is a wrapper around bam. It returns a gamViz object.

We simulate some data from the model: \[ y = f(x, z) + e, \;\;\; e \sim N(0, 2) \]

library(mgcViz)
dat <- gamSim(eg = 2, n = 1e5, dist = "normal", scale = 0.5, verbose = TRUE)
## Bivariate smoothing example
truth <- dat$truth
dat <- dat$data

image(truth$f, xlab = "x", ylab = "z")
contour(truth$x, truth$z, truth$f, add = TRUE)

Fitting Gaussian GAM using standard GAM methods:

tic <- proc.time()

fit <- gam(y ~ s(x, z, k = 100), data = dat)

( proc.time() - tic )[3]
## elapsed 
##  28.589

Fitting took few seconds, lets look at the memomy usage during estimation:

gam allocated few big memory chunks!

Fitting same GAM using Big Data methods:

tic <- proc.time()

fit <- bam(y ~ s(x, z, k = 100), data = dat, discrete = TRUE, nthreads = 2)

( proc.time() - tic )[3]
## elapsed 
##   4.157

Much faster! Lets look at memory usage:

prof <- profmem(bam(y ~ s(x, z, k = 100), data = dat, discrete = TRUE, nthreads = 2))

alloc <- prof$bytes[!is.na(prof$bytes) & prof$what == "alloc"] / 1e6
plot(alloc, ylab = "MBytes")

sum( alloc ) # MBytes
## [1] 307.3425

Memory allocation has decreased drammatically!

Working with bam and mgcViz:

fit <- bam(y ~ s(x, z, k = 100), data = dat, discrete = TRUE, nthreads = 2)
fit <- getViz(fit, nsim = 50)

Equivalent to doing:

fit <- bamV(y ~ s(x, z, k = 100),         
            data = dat,
            aGam = list(discrete = TRUE,  # arguments going to bam(). See ?bam 
                        nthreads = 2), 
            aViz = list(nsim = 50)        # arguments going to getViz(). See ?getViz
            )

Plotting the smooth effect:

plot(fit)

We can also extract the effect and plot it interactively:

plotRGL(sm(fit, 1), residuals = TRUE)

Only a sub-sample of the residuals is plotted (see ?plotRGL, maxpo argument in particular).

Plotting methods in mgcViz are meant to work with big data sets. Consider example:

x <- rnorm(1e6)
myDat <- data.frame(x = x, y = 0.5*x^2 + rnorm(1e6))

fit <- bam(y ~ s(x), data = myDat, discrete = TRUE)

Some residuals checks:

fit <- getViz(fit)

tic <- proc.time()
check(fit)   # calls check.gamViz() from mgcViz
##

the QQ-plot is discretized (see ?qq.gamViz) and the other plots show only sub-samples.

Rendering the plots produced using mgcv::gam.check might freeze your session:

tic <- proc.time()
gam.check(fit)
## 
## Method: fREML   Optimizer: perf chol
## $grad
## [1]  9.265779e-06 -9.346870e-06

because each of the \(10^6\) data points is rendered.
